e1cfd-4 | 2026-06-12T12:54:27Z | session:e1cfd663-230d-4f78-9078-0c9ed8b6a4bb | 🔍 ANALYSIS: The big strategic call was the lifecycle tap. The task named `AppDelegate.swift`, but this is a SwiftUI scene-based app — `applicationDidBecomeActive`/`DidEnterBackground` never fire when scenes are active, so those methods would have produced dead log lines. The canonical lifecycle seam already exists in `AppMain.swift`'s `scenePhase` switch next to `lifecycleForeground/Background`; I logged there. Second key decision: `append(message:)` takes an `@autoclosure` so the no-op is genuinely free — the kernel-tick string and its `library.reduce` never execute when logging is off, which matters on a hot path this repo has spent several PRs optimizing. \n  [...] **New way (iOS 13+, "scene-based"):** Apple introduced `UIScene` — the idea that an app can have multiple windows (especially on iPad). The app delegate hands lifecycle off to scene delegates. So `applicationDidBecomeActive` on `AppDelegate` **never fires** — the scene delegate methods fire instead (`sceneDidBecomeActive`, `sceneDidEnterBackground`). \n  \n SwiftUI wraps this further: you declare your scenes in `@main` / `App`, and observe `@Environment(\.scenePhase)` to get `.active` / `.background` / `.inactive`. That's what the `scenePhase` switch in `AppMain.swift` is. \n  \n **Practical upshot:** If you put lifecycle logging in `AppDelegate.applicationDidBecomeActive`, it would never print anything on this app because that method is dead code. The equivalent that actually fires is the `scenePhase == .active` branch in `AppMain.swift`.
