4dd36-8 | 2026-06-12T13:07:29Z | session:4dd36f3c-199e-4d1b-9f63-2f86c41e2f2a | Assistant: Yes, exactly that. The flow would be: \n  \n **Startup:** \n ``` \n Swift: LiteRTService.shared.loadModel("gemma4-e2b.task")  // ~2.6GB, Metal GPU \n Swift: nmp_app_register_local_llm(handle, callback_fn_ptr)  // hands Rust a fn pointer \n Rust:  stores fn ptr in PodcastHandle alongside the Tokio runtime \n ``` \n  \n **At inference time (e.g. agent chat):** \n ``` \n Swift UI  →  nmp_app_podcast_chat_complete(handle, messages_json) \n Rust:        factory.rs → local model enabled? → LocalGemmaBackend \n Rust:        LocalGemmaBackend.complete(prompt) → calls stored fn ptr \n            ↓ \n Swift:       LiteRTService.generateText(prompt)  ← blocks this thread \n              LiteRT-LM → Neural Engine / Metal GPU → tokens \n              returns String \n            ↑ \n Rust:        gets the String, runs tool loop if needed, returns {"text":"…"} \n Swift UI  ←  renders the reply \n ``` \n  \n The key thing is the callback is **synchronous from Rust's perspective** — Rust blocks a background thread waiting for Swift to return. That's fine because `chat_with_tools` already runs on a `spawn_blocking` thread, not the Tokio async scheduler. Swift's LiteRT-LM call blocks that thread for the duration of inference (~1-3 seconds for Gemma4-E2B at device speed). \n  \n **The C boundary looks like:** \n ```c \n // Swift registers at startup \n typedef char* (*NmpLocalLlmFn)(const char* prompt_json); \n void nmp_app_register_local_llm(void* handle, NmpLocalLlmFn fn); \n  \n // Rust calls when needed (fn ptr stored in handle) \n char* reply = registered_fn(prompt_json);  // blocks until inference done \n nmp_app_free_string(reply); \n ``` \n  \n **What Swift "owns" vs what Rust "owns":** \n - Swift owns: model lifecycle (download, load, unload on memory pressure), Metal GPU session, LiteRT-LM API calls \n - Rust owns: when to call it, what prompt to send, what to do with the reply, the to