55bed-4 | 2026-06-12T13:09:18Z | session:55bedfc3-dd9e-4b1c-b7d7-cea0c699d4d1 | Assistant: A projection is a read-only view of kernel state, computed on every tick and delivered to the app as part of the snapshot envelope. \n  \n Concretely: the kernel runs its state machine tick, then iterates every registered projection function, calls it with the current state, and appends the result to `KernelSnapshot::projections` under the key the app registered it with. The app receives the full envelope, pulls out its projection by key, and decodes it. \n  \n The name comes from the same idea as in event sourcing — you "project" a raw state model into a shaped, consumer-friendly view. The kernel state is the source of truth; the projection is just a derived representation of it for one specific consumer (the podcast app, in this case). \n  \n User: on every tick it recomputes a bunch of state? isn't that a performance killer? \n  \n Assistant: The kernel only emits when `changed_since_emit` is true — idle ticks produce no emission and no projection work reaches the app. So the cost is proportional to actual state changes, not wall-clock time. \n  \n The expensive part is on the Swift side: `applyKernelState` does O(N) dictionary rebuilds regardless of what changed. That's the known perf problem (~29ms with 3,615 episodes) — there's a fast-path guard being added to skip the scaffolding when no episodes changed. The projection computation in Rust itself is cheap by comparison.
