e1ab0-7 | 2026-06-12T13:14:13Z | session:e1ab0629-64bc-4383-bd22-c0843ca16a99 | ## Resume-after-interruption: the two paths differ \n  \n I checked the actual code. First, an important distinction in what "interrupted" means: \n  \n - **App backgrounded or killed** → *neither* restarts. Both use a **background `URLSession`**, so iOS's download daemon keeps transferring even while the app is suspended or terminated. Progress is not lost. \n - **Network drop / transport failure, or an explicit Cancel** → this is where they diverge: \n  \n **Episodes — yes, they resume from where they stopped.** `DownloadCapability` captures the OS's resume blob (`NSURLSessionDownloadTaskResumeData`) on failure, pause, and cancel, persists it to disk (`…/resumeData/<episode>.data`), and on the next start calls `downloadTask(withResumeData:)` — continuing from the saved byte offset instead of byte 0 (`DownloadCapability.swift:224`). Pause explicitly produces resume data via `cancel(byProducingResumeData:)`. Standard caveat: if the server doesn't honor range requests or the partial data is invalidated, URLSession silently falls back to a full restart. \n  \n **Models — no, a real interruption restarts from scratch.** `LocalModelDownloadManager.download()` always creates `session.downloadTask(with: request)` — it never uses `withResumeData:`. And its error handler just logs and sets `.notDownloaded`; it **never captures or persists the resume blob**. So on a genuine network failure (or Cancel), the next Download tap starts the 2.6–3.8 GB file over from 0. (Backgrounding/killing the app is still fine — the OS keeps going.) \n  \n So the model path has a real gap, especially painful at multi-GB sizes. The episode code already has the exact pattern to copy (persist resume data on failure → `downloadTask(withResumeData:)` on retry). [...] ## Why it's worth it (and why it's not speculative generality) \n  \n - The model **resume gap fixes itself** — models inherit episode resume/retry/background for free. \n - One source of truth for downloaded-state, disk accounting, and wifi gating across all blob types; future ones (transcripts, large artwork bundles, whatever) inherit correctness. \n - You're **deleting a known-divergent buggy duplicate**, not abstracting ahead of need. Two consumers where one is the canonical, correct implementation is exactly the right time to fold the other in. \n 
