e1ab0-9 | 2026-06-12T13:14:24Z | session:e1ab0629-64bc-4383-bd22-c0843ca16a99 | ## The Gemma model bug — fixed (PR #251) \n  \n There was one root cause behind all three symptoms you described. When a model download finished, the code tried to figure out *which* model just completed by comparing the **on-disk** filename (`gemma4-e2b`) against the **remote URL** filename (`gemma-4-E2B-it`). Those are never equal, so the match always failed and the code bailed out early — **the downloaded file was never moved into place**: \n  \n - **Stuck at 100%** — progress hit 1.0, but the "move file + mark downloaded" step silently aborted, so the row never advanced. \n - **"Download" after restart** — nothing was ever written to disk, so on relaunch the app correctly saw no file. \n - **"Cancel" with no percentage on retry** — a separate lifecycle bug: the download manager was rebuilt every time you opened the Local Models screen, which leaks the old background session (iOS only allows one per identifier) and leaves the visible screen wired to a manager that no longer receives progress callbacks. [...] - **"Cancel" with no percentage on retry** — a separate lifecycle bug: the download manager was rebuilt every time you opened the Local Models screen, which leaks the old background session (iOS only allows one per identifier) and leaves the visible screen wired to a manager that no longer receives progress callbacks. \n  [...] Assistant: Yes — and the key insight from the code is that **you've already built exactly this for episodes; the model path is the outlier that bypasses it.** So the move isn't "build a centralized download manager," it's "stop letting models be a bespoke second one." \n  \n Concretely, episode downloads already are a centralized Rust manager: \n - `apps/nmp-app-podcast/src/download/` — a real `DownloadQueue` with item states (`item.rs`: Queued → Downloading → …), concurrency slots, and policy (wifi gating, auto-download, deferred-wifi). \n - It emits `Down