8eb3f-1 | 2026-06-12T13:28:45Z | session:8eb3f00f-b245-4f03-80f0-15151d9aba28 | User: why does it take so damn long subscribe to a podcast? it always takes multiple seconds -- what is it doing? I would expect subscribing to be basically immediate and for whatever needs to happen to happen in the background (across all platforms, obviously) [...] 1. **Insert immediately**: create the podcast row from the feed *URL* (and whatever title hint the caller already has — e.g. the iTunes search result already carries title + artwork), mark it subscribed, bump rev. This makes the row appear in the library on the very next snapshot tick — sub-frame, no network. The Swift poll resolves instantly. \n 2. **Hydrate in the background**: fetch + parse the feed, merge episodes, run categorize/picks, bump rev again. The row fills in with episodes a moment later. [...] ## Why subscribing is slow \n  \n Subscribe is **synchronous and non-optimistic**. The podcast doesn't appear in your library until the *entire* RSS feed has been downloaded and parsed over the network. Nothing about it is backgrounded. \n  \n Here's the exact chain: \n  \n **1. Swift dispatches, then polls (`AppStateStore+KernelActions.swift:40-48`)** \n ```swift \n kern.dispatch(PodcastKernelAction.Subscribe(feedUrl: trimmed)) \n while ContinuousClock.now < deadline {          // up to 30s \n     if let p = podcast(feedURL: url), subscription(...) != nil { return p } \n     try await Task.sleep(for: .milliseconds(300))   // ← 300ms poll \n } \n ``` \n The UI is literally spin-waiting for the podcast to show up in the projected snapshot, checking every 300ms. \n  \n **2. The Rust kernel blocks on a full feed fetch before inserting anything (`podcast_actions_feed.rs:56-78`)** \n ```rust \n let req = build_feed_request(&url, cache.as_ref()); \n let http_result = self.dispatch_http(&req, correlation_id)?;   // ← BLOCKING network round-trip \n let result = match handle_feed_response(...) {                  // ← parse ALL episodes \n     Ok(FeedResult::Parsed { parsed, .. }) => { \n         ... \n         s.subscribe(parsed.podcast, episodes);   // ← podcast row created HERE, not before \n         self.rev.fetch_add(1, ...);              // ← only NOW does the snapshot tick \n ``` \n  \n `dispatch_http` (`dispatch.rs:29`) is a synchronous round-trip — it hands the request to the iOS/Android HTTP capability and blocks the kernel action thread until the response comes back. So the podcast row literally does not exist until: full RSS XML downloaded (often hundreds of KB to several MB for shows with long back-catalogs) → parsed into every episode → store write → rev bump → snapshot projected → Swift's next 300ms poll catches it. \n  \n **3. Then it does *more* synchronous work on the same path (`:120-123`)** — `auto_categorize()` and `auto_refresh_picks()` run inline after the subscribe before the dispatch returns. \n  \n So your "multiple seconds" ≈ feed download time + parse time + up to 300ms poll jitter. Slow/large feeds are the worst case, and there's zero optimistic feedback. [...] ## What was wrong \n  \n `handle_subscribe` ran on the kernel actor thread and **synchronously downloaded + parsed the entire RSS feed before inserting the podcast row** (the HTTP capability blocks the actor thread per ADR-0023). So the library didn't update until the whole feed finished — multiple seconds, no feedback. \n 
