ion callers are `handle_refresh` and `handle_refresh_all` (`host_op_handler/podcast_actions_refresh.rs:49,82`). I verified via `git grep` there are no other call sites. \n  \n **The gap — episodes that need triage but get none because no feed refresh follows their appearance:** \n  \n 1. **Cold launch (most serious).** The iOS app *explicitly skips* `RefreshAll` on the first foreground (`App/Sources/Bridge/KernelModel.swift:448-461`; the `hasObservedForeground` guard and its own comment: "Cold start skips `RefreshAll`"). At cold start the store loads episodes from disk and the triage cache is restored via `set_data_dir` (`ffi/data_dir.rs:118`, correctly repointed to `state.inbox.triage_cache`). Any episode that is un-triaged (cache miss) or whose `Ready` entry is now stale (`>24h`, `TRIAGE_STALE_SECS`) satisfies `episodes_needing_triage`, but **nothing fires it**. Under the old code the first post-launch snapshot rebuild triaged them; now they sit untriaged (heuristic fallback only) until the user backgrounds→foregrounds or pulls to refresh AND a feed returns new episodes. \n  \n 2. **Stale-`Pending` retry after a failed pass.** `TRIAGE_RETRY_COOLDOWN_SECS = 10 min`. A failed triage (e.g. Ollama offline) stamps episodes `Pending`. Old code retried on the next snapshot rebuild after the 10-min cooldown — which happens constantly while the app is in use. New code only retries on the next feed refresh. If the user keeps the app foregrounded and Ollama recovers, those episodes are never re-triaged within the session. \n  \n 3. **Fresh subscribe / OPML import.** `handle_subscribe` (and `handle_import_opml`, which loops `handle_subscribe`) do NOT call `maybe_enqueue_triage`; new episodes land asynchronously via `http_report`. Old code triaged them on the next rebuild; new code does not until a later refresh. \n  \n Note also: `handle_refresh_all` gates the trigger on `any_succeeded` (`podcast_actions_refresh.rs:80-84`), so a foreground refresh where every feed returns 304 (common) bumps rev but does **not** fire triage — even though stale `Ready`/`Pending` entries may still need it. \n  \n ### Minimal fix (pick the cheapest that closes scenario 1, ideally all three) \n - **Add a launch/foreground trigger.** Fire `self.state.inbox.maybe_enqueue_triage()` on the cold-start path — e.g. from the `auto_download_evaluate` op the app already dispatches at first foreground (`KernelModel.swift:457`), or add an explicit launch hook. This is the must-have. \n - **Decouple `refresh_all`'s trigger from `any_succeeded`** so a 304-only refresh still re-evaluates triage. \n - Optionally also trigger after `http_report` applies new episodes (covers subscribe/OPML). \n  \n It is intentionally cheap because `maybe_enqueue_triage` is internally guarded — calling it more often is a no-op when nothing is needed. The whole point of the old per-rebuild placement was breadth of coverage; the new placement is too narrow. \n  \n ### Everything else — confirmed fine \n - **Substate migration (#2):** correct. 3 fields gone from both `ffi/handle.rs` and `host_op_handler.rs`; seeded in `PodcastAppState::new` (`state/mod.rs:271`). Lock topology preserved — off-actor tokio writers still reach `triage_cache` via `Slot::share()` → `Arc<Mutex<_>>` (`state/inbox.rs:113-117,135-156`). `set_data_dir` cold-load repointed correctly. Rev/signal discipline intact (`infra.signal`/`infra.rev` threaded through `handle`/`maybe_enqueue_triage`). No half-migrated state. `triage_in_progress` correctly kept as a bare `Arc<AtomicBool>` outside the `Slot` abstraction. \n - **D8 guard (#3):** `project()` is pure (`state/inbox.rs:106-118`), and `project_does_not_set_triage_in_progress` genuinely asserts no `in_progress` claim after calling the snapshot path — it proves the side effect is gone. \n - **Golden change (#4):** independently confirmed — the 3821→3789 diff is *byte-identical* except the removed trailing `,"inbox_triage_in_progress":true`. Nothing else drifted. This is the correct consequence of making the projection pure. Golden test passes. \n - **Health (#5):** `state/inbox.rs` is 339 LOC (under the 500 ceiling) and clippy-clean. All 46 inbox tests + the golden test pass. No nmp-core change. Remaining clippy `too many arguments (8/7)` warnings are pre-existing on the unchanged free functions, not introduced here. (One cosmetic nit: a stray blank line added before the closing brace in `host_op_handler.rs` — harmless.) \n  \n **Bottom line:** the refactor is well-executed but silently narrows triage from "whenever the snapshot rebuilds" to "only after a successful feed refresh," and the iOS app deliberately does not refresh at cold launch. That is a behavioral regression for proactive triage. Add an app-launch/foreground triage trigger (and ideally decouple `refresh_all` from `any_succeeded`) before merge. \n 
