e. The only publisher datum the parser intentionally drops is the chapters MIME (always the constant `application/json+chapters`), which is non-load-bearing. No field that carries data is lost. \n  \n ### 2. Observer registration — SOUND (before interest, truly once) \n `nostr_episodes.rs::handle_subscribe_nostr` (lines 100–155): `OBSERVER_REGISTERED.get_or_init(...)` runs and returns synchronously **before** `subscribe_nostr_episodes` → `push_interest_via_nmp` → `app.push_interest` (`nmp_dispatch.rs:97`). Since relay events only arrive asynchronously on the actor thread after the interest opens, the observer is provably registered before the first kind:54 can be delivered — no EOSE-sweep drop. `OnceLock::get_or_init` guarantees single execution under concurrent first calls. The `register_event_observer(Arc::new(...))→drop(id)` shape exactly matches the five existing observers in `ffi/register.rs:287–325`, and `KernelEvent` field access (`kind/id/author/created_at as i64/content/tags`) matches `comments_handler.rs:192–227` and `discover_nostr.rs:203–216`. It is interest-driven and reactive — no polling. \n  \n **Follow-up (non-blocking):** the `get_or_init` closure no-ops registration when `app.is_null()` (`nostr_episodes.rs:128`) yet still marks the `OnceLock` initialized, so a later valid-`app` call would never register. In production `app` is non-null for the process lifetime, so this cannot occur — but a guard (only seal the OnceLock on a non-null app) would harden it. \n  \n ### 3. Feedless store row integrity — CORRECT \n `store/library.rs:347` / `383` derive `PodcastId = UUIDv5(NAMESPACE_URL, "nostr:show:{pubkey}")` — deterministic and stable. RSS shows use `PodcastId::generate` = UUIDv4 random (`podcast_actions_feed.rs:64`), so collisions are impossible. A kind:54 from pubkey X always resolves to the same id and is routed by `podcast_id_for_pubkey` matching `owner_pubkey_hex` (`library.rs:336`) — it cannot land in another show's row. `Podcast::new` sets `fee