c1691-124 | 2026-06-12T15:46:55Z | session:c1691db0-d63e-4062-adad-1cfa0d679d09 | ## Tier 0 — Correctness / stability (I'd do these first) \n  \n **0.1 — No `catch_unwind` on FFI entry points that `block_on` network/LLM futures.** *(crash class)* \n The crate has **zero** `catch_unwind`, builds as `cdylib`, and has no `panic = "abort"`. Actor-path panics are caught upstream by nmp_core — but the *direct* `extern "C"` entries (`ffi/chat_complete.rs:179`, `provider_complete.rs`, `provider_embeddings`, `perplexity_search`, `elevenlabs_scribe`, `openrouter_whisper`, `byok_auth.rs:40`, plus the JNI entries in `android.rs`) drive futures via `runtime.block_on(...)` with no guard. A panic in any of those futures (a downstream `.unwrap()`, a parser overflow, a reqwest/serde edge) unwinds across the C ABI → UB/abort, crashing the shell. \n **Fix:** one shared `ffi_guard<T>(fallback, f)` helper wrapping each entry, returning the file's existing degrade value (null / `{"error":"panic"}`) on catch. **Effort M, risk low, payoff high.** Also worth pairing with `[profile.release] panic = "abort"` so even an unguarded path is a *defined* abort, not UB. [...] **0.1 — two real errors in my framing.** \n - "UB across the C ABI" is **wrong on this toolchain**. Since rustc 1.81, a panic escaping `extern "C"` is a *deterministic abort*, not UB — still a crash, but one severity notch down. \n - My `panic="abort"` suggestion is **self-defeating** and should be rejected: it would no-op the proposed `ffi_guard` *and* nullify upstream nmp_core's `catch_unwind` around the actor tick — turning today's "actor panics are caught" into process death. Good catch. \n - The entry list was **incomplete** (missed `elevenlabs_tts`, `assemblyai_transcript`, `provider_key_validation`, `provider_model_catalog`, `elevenlabs_voice_catalog`). Right fix: guard the whole `src/ffi/` module, not a named list. [...] User: [Agent task result: Agent "Impl: ffi_guard catch_unwind fan-out" completed] \n All done. Here is the report. \n  \n ## Report \n  \n **New helper signature** (`apps/nmp-app-podcast/src/ffi/guard.rs`): \n ```rust \n pub(crate) fn ffi_guard<T>( \n     site: &str, \n     fallback: impl FnOnce() -> T, \n     body: impl FnOnce() -> T, \n ) -> T { \n     match catch_unwind(AssertUnwindSafe(body)) { \n         Ok(val) => val, \n         Err(_) => { \n             log::error!("ffi_guard: caught panic at {site}; returning fallback sentinel"); \n             fallback() \n         } \n     } \n } \n ``` \n The fallback is now lazy — constructed only on the `Err(_)` (panic) path. \n  \n **All call sites use closures — grep proof:** \n - A balanced-paren parser inspected all 57 `ffi_guard(` calls across the crate: **every** second argument starts with `||`. ("ALL fallbacks are closures. OK.") \n - The targeted grep for eager allocating fallbacks (`into_raw()` / `_envelope(` / `static_error(` on a fallback line lacking `||`) returns **empty**. \n - The `bin/headless/capability_host.rs` inline `catch_unwind` variant had the identical leak (its `{"error":"panic"}` CString was built before `body`); now built in the `Err(_)` arm only. \n - 21 multi-line + 35 single-line `ffi_guard` sites + 1 capability-callback site wrapped; the 11 trivial `|| std::ptr::null_mut()` fallbacks were converted to the bare fn path `std::ptr::null_mut` to avoid introducing `clippy::redundant_closure`. \n  \n **No-leak success-path test:** `success_path_never_invokes_fallback_closure` — the fallback closure flips a `static AtomicBool`; the test asserts it is NEVER set when `body` returns `Ok`, directly proving the fallback isn't constructed on success. Complemented by `panic_path_invokes_fallback_closure_exactly_once`. Both pass; all 11 guard-module tests green. \n  \n **Site-logging wiring:** the `Err(_)` arm emits `log::error!("ffi_guard: caught panic at {site}; …")` (matching the crate's existing `log::warn!` usage in `host_op_handler/router.rs`). Cheap, lazy-formatted, never on the success path. The headless variant uses `eprintln!` similarly. \n  \n **Rebase + test + golden + clippy status:** \n - Rebase: `origin/main` (`6538515b`) already an ancestor — "up to date," no replay needed. Force-with-lease pushed (`0f2b8f75..7a89575a`). \n - Tests: `1191 passed; 0 failed; 7 ignored` (was 1183 — +8 from new/modified guard tests). \n - Golden: `snapshot_bytes_match_golden_fixture` passes — byte-identical, projections untouched. \n - Clippy: total dropped 54→43; **zero** lints remain in any touched FFI/android file; no new lints vs baseline. \n - PR #387: **OPEN**, auto-merge **off** (`autoMerge: null`); review-response comment posted. \n  [...] # Verdict: REQUEST-CHANGES \n  \n The panic-guard design is sound and the implementation is careful in almost every respect — but it introduces a **systematic memory leak on the success path of ~16 string-returning `extern "C"` FFI entries**. This is a real correctness regression that ships to iOS hot paths, so it must be fixed before merge. \n  \n ## THE BLOCKER — success-path CString leak (the crux, but not the way the prompt framed it) \n  \n The fallback values are *value-correct* (they match each function's prior error sentinel — see table below). The defect is in the **allocation lifecycle**, not the value. \n  \n Rust evaluates function arguments eagerly. For every entry whose fallback is `err_envelope("panic").into_raw()` / `static_error("panic", …).into_raw()`, the CString is allocated and **leaked via `into_raw()` before `body` even runs**. On the panic path that's correct (the leaked pointer becomes the return value; the Swift caller frees it via `nmp_app_free_string`). But on the **no-panic path** — i.e. essentially every call — `ffi_guard` returns `Ok(val) => val` and the `fallback: *mut c_char` parameter is dropped. Dropping a raw pointer is a no-op, so the fallback's heap allocation is **never reclaimed**. These functions did not leak before this PR. \n  \n Leak set (18 call sites, confirmed via grep): \n - `ffi/provider_complete.rs:21`, `provider_embeddings.rs:21`, `chat_complete.rs:144` — per-LLM-turn / per-RAG-chunk (hottest) \n - `ffi/assemblyai_transcript.rs:23`, `elevenlabs_scribe.rs:21`, `elevenlabs_tts.rs:21`, `openrouter_whisper.rs:21`, `perplexity_search.rs:21`, `image_generation.rs:45`, `rerank.rs:88` \n - `ffi/byok_auth.rs:18,43`, `provider_key_validation.rs:21,44`, `provider_model_catalog.rs:20`, `speech_model_catalog.rs:17`, `local_model_catalog.rs:19`, `elevenlabs_voice_catalog.rs:20` \n - `bin/headless/capability_host.rs:64` — same inline pattern (lower severity, headless test binary) \n  \n Fix: make the fallback non-allocating-until-needed. Easiest is to change `ffi_guard` to take `fallback: impl FnOnce() -> T` (lazy), or have the string entries pass a sentinel that is materialized to a raw pointer *inside* the `Err(_)` arm. The null-ptr / scalar / void fallbacks (snapshot.rs, audio_report.rs, all of android.rs, reports.rs) are fine as-is because their fallbacks don't allocate. \n  \n ## #1 Per-entry fallback table (value-correctness — all MATCH) \n  \n | Entry | Return | Fallback | Prior sentinel | Verdict | \n |---|---|---|---|---| \n | `nmp_app_podcast_snapshot` | `*mut c_char` | `null_mut()` | null on CString err | MATCH | \n | `nmp_app_podcast_decode_update_frame` | `*mut c_char` | `null_mut()` | `Err(_) => null` on bad frame (never a JSON string) | MATCH | \n | `nmp_app_podcast_snapshot_rev` | `u64` | `0u64` | `0` on null handle | MATCH | \n | `nmp_app_podcast_snapshot_free` / `unregister` | `()` | `()` | void | MATCH | \n | `nmp_app_podcast_provider_complete` | `*mut c_char` | `err_envelope("panic")` | always `{"error":…}`, never null | value MATCH / **leaks** | \n | `nmp_app_podcast_chat_complete` | `*mut c_char` | `err_envelope("panic")` | always `{"error":…}` (D6: never NULL) | value MATCH / **leaks** | \n | `nmp_app_podcast_rerank` | `*mut c_char` | `static_error("panic",…)` | typed `{"error":{kind,…}}` | value MATCH / **leaks** | \n | `nmp_app_podcast_assemblyai_transcribe` | `*mut c_char` | `err_envelope("panic",None,"panic")` | typed error envelope | value MATCH / **leaks** | \n | `nmp_app_podcast_register` | `*mut PodcastHandle` | `null_mut()` | null on null app; caller null-checks at registration | MATCH | \n | JNI `nativeChatComplete` etc. | `jstring` | `null` | null jstring = failure on Kotlin side | MATCH | \n | JNI `nmpActionDispatch` | `jint` | `-1` | `-1` documented failure code | MATCH | \n | JNI `nativeNew` | `jlong` | `0` | 0 = failure handle | MATCH | \n  \n So the panic-path *observable value* is correct everywhere — no entry changes a previously-valid-JSON-error into a null. The only behavioral regression is the leak, not the sentinel. \n  \n ## #2 Coverage — COMPLETE \n  \n Every `#[no_mangle]` entry is guarded. Verified the apparent gap in `provider_transport.rs` (16 JNI entries, only 3 `ffi_guard` calls): those 16 entries are pure delegation to 3 shared helpers (`call_podcast_json_ffi`, `call_podcast_global_json_ffi`, `call_podcast_catalog_ffi`), each of which wraps its full body in `ffi_guard` — so all 16 are covered, and the underlying `extern "C"` targets are independently guarded too. `capability_host.rs` legitimately uses inline `catch_unwind` because `pub(crate) ffi_guard` isn't reachable from a `[[bin]]` crate. No unwrapped entries. (`provider_transport.rs:25-27` and `llm/local_model_backend.rs:19` are type aliases / fn-pointer types, not entries.) \n  \n ## #3 AssertUnwindSafe soundness — SOUND \n  \n Args are null-checked-before-closure raw ptrs + `&PodcastHandle` (`Arc<Mutex<…>>`); a mid-body panic poisons a Mutex, which is the app-wide-tolerated D6 degrade. The report-writeback path (`nativeCapabilityReport` → `audio_report` → PlayerActor projection) leaves no broken-beyond-poison shared state. The module doc's three-point justification is accurate. \n  \n ## #4 Observability gap — FOLLOW-UP (not a blocker) \n  \n `let _ = site` swallows every caught panic with zero tel