N="platform=iOS Simulator,id=$udid" \n fi \n ``` \n  \n The destination is now passed by UDID (`platform=iOS Simulator,id=<udid>`) rather than by name, which is more robust. `-skipPackagePluginValidation` and the rest of the xcodebuild invocation are unchanged.
c1691-153 | 2026-06-12T22:03:19Z | session:c1691db0-d63e-4062-adad-1cfa0d679d09 |  \n Since #377 (v0.3.0 typed-first migration), `signed_events` moved from the JSON projections map to a typed FlatBuffer sidecar. The iOS `SignedEventsRegistry.ingest` still read `v.projections["signed_events"]` from the JSON output of `nmp_app_podcast_decode_update_frame` — which never populated that key from the typed sidecar. Every `nmp_app_sign_event_for_return` result was silently dropped, breaking NIP-46 / active-account signing. \n  \n **What changed (commit `468562bc`)** \n  \n - `apps/nmp-app-podcast/src/ffi/snapshot.rs`: Added `decode_signed_events_sidecar(slice: &[u8]) -> Option<serde_json::Value>` using nmp-core v0.4.0 symbols `decode_snapshot_typed_projections` + `typed_projections::decode_signed_events` + `SIGNED_EVENTS_SCHEMA_ID`. The function is called immediately after building `v` from the `SnapshotEnvelope`; on success it injects under `v["projections"]["signed_events"]`. Full D6 compliance: any decode failure returns `None` silently, no panic. \n  \n - `apps/nmp-app-podcast/src/ffi/snapshot_decode_tests.rs` (new, linked via `#[path]`): 5 tests covering absent sidecar, malformed payload (D6), live kernel end-to-end (empty pubkey → `ok=false` result), golden no-projections-key, and integration that `v.projections.signed_events` is populated. [...]  \n **File:** `apps/nmp-app-podcast/src/host_op_handler/podcast_actions_feed.rs` lines 175–182 \n  \n **Before:** \n ```rust \n if let Ok(mut s) = self.store.lock() { \n     s.update_refresh_metadata(podcast_id, etag_out, lm_out); \n     self.rev.fetch_add(1, Ordering::Relaxed);  // ← unconditional \n } \n ``` \n  \n **After:** `rev.fetch_add` removed; only `update_refresh_metadata` runs. A 2-line comment explains the intent. \n  \n **304 no-bump test result:** \n ``` \n test host_op_handler::podcast_actions_feed::feed_304_tests::rev_unchanged_on_304 ... ok \n test host_op_handler::podcast_actions_feed::feed_304_tests::rev_bumped_on_parsed_feed ... ok \n ``` \n Both new tests pass. `refresh_one` (periodic background refresh) already had the correct no-bump behaviour — `handle_ensure_podcast` now matches it. \n  [...] ## The domain-mapping approach (one-place mapping) \n  \n I used the reviewer's preferred "Domain on the Infra handle" design. There are exactly **two single-source maps**, no per-call-site scatter: \n - **`Domain → counter`**: `DomainRevs::counter` (extracted to new `state/domain.rs`) \n - **`Domain → substate`**: `PodcastAppState::new_with_identity` hands each substate a domain-scoped `Infra` via `infra.with_domain(Domain::X)`. `Infra::bump` now reads `self.domain` and advances both that domain's counter and the global rev — so a substate's existing bare `self.infra.bump()` routes correctly with **zero call-site churn**. Scoped: PlaybackState→Playback, CategoriesState→Library, everything else→Misc (default). \n  \n ## bump_domain wiring at mutation sites \n  \n The host-op handler holds the root (Misc) Infra, so its arms can't use scope. I added one handler-side mechanism, `PodcastHostOpHandler::bump_domain(Domain)`, and replaced every raw `self.state.infra.rev.fetch_add(1, …)` with a domain-tagged call across settings_actions (41), player_actions (Playback/Downloads), podcast_actions (Library/Settings), downloads (Downloads/Library), feed + refresh + dispatch (Library), plus `IdentityHandler::with_domain_rev` (Identity) and the cross-thread audio/download report FFIs (Library + Playback). I also moved `inbox` into the library payload since it's derived from library episodes. \n  \n ## End-to-end test result (the proof requested) \n  \n ``` \n test ...::real_queue_mutation_bumps_only_playback_domain ... ok \n test ...::real_settings_mutation_bumps_only_settings_domain ... ok \n ``` \n A real `podcast.player.enqueue` through the actual handler advances **only** the playback domain rev (library + settings unchanged); `set_skip_intervals` advances **only** settings. Combined with the existing `playback_tick_excludes_library_sidecar` (frame omits the library sidecar), this proves a real playback change produces a frame with the playback sidecar and **without** the library sidecar. \n  \n ## Rebase + golden status \n  \n Branched off current `origin/main` (post-#396/#399 merge), so the dead gated projection is already gone — nothing to drop. Golden fixture **3789 bytes, byte-identical** (pull path untouched). `cargo test -p nmp-app-podcast`: **1213 passed, 0 failed, 7 ignored**. clippy: 54 warnings vs baseline 56 (no new warnings; removed two dead items). `state/mod.rs` was split to `state/domain.rs` to stay under the 500-LOC ceiling (558→464). No nmp-core change; `App/` and `android/` untouched. \n  [...]  \n - **iOS:** `KernelBridge.decode(pointer:)` (`App/Sources/Bridge/KernelBridge.swift:234-256`) still requires `v.projections["podcast.snapshot"]`. Since NMP v0.3.0 typed-first the generic projections map is never encoded, and #396 deleted that registration. **Every push frame fails decode** ("snapshot frame missing podcast.snapshot projection") and `sink.handler` never fires. iOS today is 100% pull-driven: report-channel hooks + `pullPodcastSnapshotIfChanged` (full multi-MB Rust serialize + full off-main decode per change). Background rev bumps (triage completion, async feed hydration) surface only when an audio report or user dispatch happens to probe. \n - **Android:** worse. `SnapshotCodec.decodeEnvelope` (`PodcastSnapshot.kt:503-525`) decodes the slim `v` (`rev`/`running`/`schema_version` only — see `nmp_app_podcast_decode_update_frame`, `ffi/snapshot.rs:356+`) directly as `PodcastSnapshot`. Every field is defaulted, so decode **succeeds with an empty library** and `MainActivity.kt:152-157` does `snapshot = next` — every kernel emit **clobbers the UI to an empty state**. This is an active correctness bug, masked only by how rarely frames emit while idle. \n - **Kernel contract gap found:** in `ffi/snapshot_domain_projections.rs`, when a domain rev advances but the builder returns `None` (empty state — library/downloads/identity/widget), `last_emitted` is NOT advanced and no tombstone is emitted. Consequences: (a) a shell consuming sidecars can never learn "downloads cleared / signed out / unsubscribed-all"; (b) an empty domain re-runs `build_podcast_update` (full snapshot build, store lock) **every tick forever**. A small Rust fix (emit `{"rev":N, "<field>":null}` and advance `last_emitted`) is required before shells can rely on sidecars. Also note: each domain builder calls full `build_podcast_update` per changed domain per tick (up to 7 full builds/tick) — acceptable post-#267 (~7.6ms), flag as kernel follow-up, not a blocker. [...] - **Android:** worse. `SnapshotCodec.decodeEnvelope` (`PodcastSnapshot.kt:503-525`) decodes the slim `v` (`rev`/`running`/`schema_version` only — see `nmp_app_podcast_decode_update_frame`, `ffi/snapshot.rs:356+`) directly as `PodcastSnapshot`. Every field is defaulted, so decode **succeeds with an empty library** and `MainActivity.kt:152-157` does `snapshot = next` — every kernel emit **clobbers the UI to an empty state**. This is an active correctness bug, masked only by how rarely frames emit while idle. \n - **Kernel contract gap found:** in `ffi/snapshot_domain_projections.rs`, when a domain rev advances but the builder returns `None` (empty state — library/downloads/identity/widget), `last_emitted` is NOT advanced and no tombstone is emitted. Consequences: (a) a shell consuming sidecars can never learn "downloads cleared / signed out / unsubscribed-all"; (b) an empty domain re-runs `build_podcast_update` (full snapshot build, store lock) **every tick forever**. A small Rust fix (emit `{"rev":N, "<field>":null}` and advance `last_emitted`) is required before shells can rely on sidecars. Also note: each domain builder calls full `build_podcast_update` per changed domain per tick (up to 7 full builds/tick) — acceptable post-#267 (~7.6ms), flag as kernel follow-up, not a blocker. \n  [...] ### Decode change (quoted) \n  \n Before: \n ```swift \n guard let update = Self.decodePodcastUpdate(envelopePayload: data) else { \n     kbLog.error("snapshot frame missing podcast.snapshot projection bytes=\(data.count)") \n     return nil \n } \n ``` \n  \n After: \n ```swift \n guard let domainFrames = PodcastDomainFrames.decode(from: data) else { \n     kbLog.error("snapshot frame missing all podcast.* domain sidecars bytes=\(data.count)") \n     return nil \n } \n ``` \n  \n `KernelUpdateResult` now carries `domainFrames: PodcastDomainFrames` instead of `update: PodcastUpdate`. \n  \n ### KernelDomainFrames.swift — one envelope (confirming NO explicit CodingKeys) \n  \n ```swift \n struct PlaybackDomainFrame: Decodable { \n     var rev: UInt64 = 0 \n     var nowPlaying: PlayerState? \n     var queue: [EpisodeSummary]? \n } \n ``` \n  \n No `CodingKeys` enum. `now_playing` → `nowPlaying` and `queue` via `.convertFromSnakeCase` exactly as the #371 contract requires. \n  \n ### Composite merge + per-domain observable assignment + drop-guard \n  \n `KernelModel` holds: \n - `compositeUpdate: PodcastUpdate` — the merged state from selective domain updates \n - `domainRevTracker: DomainRevTracker` — per-domain last-applied rev for drop-guard \n  \n In `apply(result:)`: \n 1. `mergeDomainFrames(_:into:tracker:)` iterates each present domain, compares `frame.rev > tracker.<domain>`, merges only accepted domains, returns `Bool` (any accepted) \n 2. If accepted: `compositeUpdate.rev = max(domain revs)`, `compositeUpdate.running = true`, then `applyPodcastUpdate(compositeUpdate, fromPull: false)` \n 3. Identity: only updated when `result.identity != .empty` (identity domain was present this frame) — preserves prior `kernelIdentity` when identity didn't change \n  \n ### Tombstone handling \n  \n Domain envelopes use `decodeIfPresent` throughout. A frame like `{"rev":99,"active_account":null}` decodes with `activeAccount == nil` (logged-out state). The `mergeDomainFrames` method assigns `composite.activeAccount = ident.activeAccount` (nil = logged out) when the domain's rev advances. \n  \n ### Wire tests \n  \n `KernelBridgeWireTests.swift` gained 9 new test methods: \n 1. `testPlaybackDomainFrameDecodesViaKernelDecodingSeam` — snake_case `episode_id` → `episodeId` \n 2. `testLibraryDomainFrameDecodesViaKernelDecodingSeam` — `is_subscribed` → `isSubscribed` \n 3. `testIdentityDomainFrameDecodesActiveAccountViaSnakeCaseConversion` — `pubkey_hex` → `pubkeyHex` \n 4. `testMultiDomainFrameDecodesAllPresentDomains` \n 5. `testPlaybackOnlyFrameDoesNotClearLibrarySliceInComposite` — core delta-transport assertion \n 6. `testIdentityTombstoneFrameClearsActiveAccount` — `active_account: null` → `activeAccount == nil` \n 7. `testDropGuardIgnoresStaleRevFrame` — rev=3 after rev=5 accepted → composite unchanged \n 8. `testAbsentDomainFrameYieldsNil` — D6 degrade \n 9. `testDomainSchemaConstantsMatchKernelSchemaIDs` \n  \n **What was run**: `xcodebuild build -scheme Podcastr -destination "generic/platform=iOS Simulator" -skipPackagePluginValidation` — zero Swift errors. Build fails only at the linker (missing Rust dylib for this worktree — expected). Could not run the sim tests because the Rust dylib is not built in this worktree. Tests are structured for `xcodebuild test -only-testing:PodcastrTests/KernelBridgeWireTests` once the dylib is available. \n  \n **PR**: https://github.com/pablof7z/podcast-player/pull/403 — left open for review. [...] Independent review complete. This PR fully removes the empty-library clobber bug and ships the Android per-domain push-consumption half as a faithful twin of the already-approved iOS #403. I read every changed file plus the Rust emitter and the iOS twin for cross-checking. \n  \n ### 1. Clobber removed + cold-start — FULLY FIXED, no blank-library path remains \n - The old `decodeFromJsonElement(PodcastSnapshot.serializer(), v)` path is **gone** — the entire `decodeEnvelope` + `SnapshotEnvelope` block was deleted from `PodcastSnapshot.kt` (diff lines 487–535 removed). The slim `v` is never again decoded as a full snapshot. \n - `MainActivity.kt:166-172` applies `snapshot = merged` **only when `anyAccepted == true`**. A frame with no domains returns `null` from `decodeDomainFrames` (the `if (!frames.hasAnyDomain) null` guard, `DomainFrames.kt`), hits `?: continue`, and never touches state. A frame whose domains are all stale yields `anyAccepted=false` → no assignment. \n - Cold-start hydrator is intact: `MainActivity.kt:140-148` still does the one-shot `bridge.podcastSnapshot()` PULL → `SnapshotCodec.decode` (the full-snapshot decoder, retained). The grid paints on launch. \n - Absent domains are merged via `copy()` touching only present slices — they are never cleared. **The empty-clobber is fully removed, not narrowed.** There is no remaining path where a push frame blanks the library: blanking now requires an explicit library tombstone (`{"rev":N,"library":null}`) at a higher rev, which is the intended all-unsubscribed signal. \n  \n ### 2. Schema symmetry — `@SerialName` ↔ Rust emitted fields (per-domain table) \n  \n Rust emitter: `apps/nmp-app-podcast/src/ffi/snapshot_domain_projections.rs`. `ignoreUnknownKeys = true` is set (`DomainFrames.kt` SnapshotCodec.json), so Rust-only fields are safely dropped on Android. All Kotlin domain-frame fields are nullable/defaulted → no missing-required throw risk. \n  \n | Domain | Rust emits | Kotlin `@SerialName` | Match | \n |---|---|---|---| \n | library | rev, library, categories, search_results, nostr_results, owned_podcasts, inbox, inbox_triage_in_progress | rev, library, `search_results`, inbox, `inbox_triage_in_progress` | ✅ (categories/nostr_results/owned_podcasts intentionally not modeled on Android — no top-level field exists, same as iOS-renders-only superset; harmless via ignoreUnknownKeys) | \n | playback | rev, now_playing, queue | rev, `now_playing`, queue | ✅ | \n | downloads | rev, downloads | rev, downloads | ✅ | \n | settings | rev, settings, configured_relays | rev, settings | ✅ (configured_relays not modeled on Android, as in base snapshot) | \n | identity | rev, active_account | rev, `active_account` | ✅ | \n | widget | rev, widget | rev, widget | ✅ | \n | misc | rev, +15 fields | rev, `agent_tasks`, `feedback_events`, `feedback_threads`, voice, agent | ✅ subset (wiki/picks/clips/social/etc. not rendered on Android) | \n  \n Nested types (`NowPlayingState`, `DownloadQueueSnapshot`, `EpisodeSummary`, `PodcastSummary`, `AccountSummary`, `WidgetSnapshot`, `InboxItem`) are **unchanged, pre-existing** types already proven by the working cold-start `decode` pull path; the domain frames reuse them, inheriting correct `@SerialName`s. No mismatch found. \n  \n ### 3. Tombstone handling — correct \n `coerceInputValues = true` does **not** corrupt tombstones because every tombstone primary field is nullable (`library: List<...>? = null`, `downloads`, `activeAccount`, `widget`) — null stays null, no throw. Merge maps: library null → `emptyList()`, identity null → `activeAccount = null` (signed out), downloads null → `downloads = null`, widget null → `widget = null`. Matches the Rust tombstone shapes exactly. \n  \n ### 4. Drop guard + merge — correct \n Per-domain `frame.rev > tracker[domain]` monotonic guard; `copy()` replaces only accepted domains. Sidecar `rev` is the global rev (Rust `update.rev` for all domains) — same as iOS. Tracker is `remember { DomainRevTracker() }`, resetting to all-0 on process restart; combined with the cold-start pull (which sets full state without advancing the tracker), the first post-launch push for each domain is accepted and merges identical-or-newer data over the pulled snapshot — no drop, no clobber. \n  \n ### 5. Hygiene \n Android-only: diff stat is 3 Kotlin files (`DomainFrames.kt` new, `MainActivity.kt` +20/-8, `PodcastSnapshot.kt` -51 codec removal). No Rust/JNI change. All merge targets (`agentTasks`, `feedbackEvents`, `feedbackThreads`, `voice`, `agent`, etc.) exist on `PodcastSnapshot`. The `MainActivity` edit is minimal and localized to the frame loop (lines 151-173) plus one tracker declaration — it will not conflict heavily with the uncommitted identity WIP in the shared root (that WIP is in the DisposableEffect/identity-restore block, a different region). \n  \n ### Optional follow-up (non-blocking) \n No Android-side wire fixture test exists (iOS has `KernelBridgeWireTests.swift`). The MEMORY note "demand Rust-JSON→bridge-decoder fixture tests" applies — an Android instrumentation/unit test feeding a captured `{"t":"snapshot","v":{"projections":{...}}}` fixture through `decodeDomainFrames`/`mergeFrames` would lock the snake_case contract against future Rust field renames. Recommend as a fast-follow, not a merge blocker, since this PR is a twin of validated iOS code and decodes a strict subset of already-proven nested types. \n  \n Ship it. \n  [...]  \n **Change (quoted):** \n ```swift \n // KernelModel.swift — new property \n private var hasHydrated: Bool = false \n  \n // applyPodcastUpdate — new guard \n let revPasses = fromPull && !hasHydrated \n     ? update.rev >= Int(lastProcessedRev) \n     : update.rev > Int(lastProcessedRev) \n guard revPasses else { return } \n lastProcessedRev = UInt64(update.rev) \n if fromPull { \n     compositeUpdate = update \n     hasHydrated = true   // ← steady-state guard restored from here on \n } \n ``` \n  \n `resetAndRestart()` also resets `hasHydrated = false` so a kernel reset gets the same cold-start allowance. No steady-state behaviour change — once the first full pull lands, the normal `>` monotonic guard is in effect for all subsequent push and pull frames. \n 
