c1691-166 | 2026-06-12T22:25:33Z | session:c1691db0-d63e-4062-adad-1cfa0d679d09 |  \n **What/why:** Replace "one global rev → full-library re-serialize + full-frame decode on any change" with per-domain push deltas. A `PersistPosition` tick (~1/30s) or download-progress report then ships ~1KB of playback/downloads JSON instead of triggering a multi-MB pull+decode. This is the 10x-scale fix the wiki explicitly calls for, and it deletes the four accreted mitigations' root cause. \n **Wiki:** `docs/wiki/change-gate-projections.md` ("Domain Revision Tracking", "Domain Sub-Projections"), `kernel-snapshot-emission.md`, `android-snapshot-push.md`, `reactive-update-model.md`. \n **Scope: L**, staged as 4 independently-landable PRs: \n  \n - **PR-1 (S, ship day 1):** Delete the dead `register_snapshot_projection_gated("podcast.snapshot", …)` block in `apps/nmp-app-podcast/src/ffi/register.rs`. Zero consumer risk (verified above); immediate actor-thread CPU win. Pull path untouched. \n - **PR-2 (M-L, the long pole, Rust-only):** Per-domain revs + producers. \n   - `src/state/mod.rs`: `Infra` currently carries ONE global `rev: Arc<AtomicU64>` cloned into all 15 substates. Add a per-domain rev (e.g. `DomainRevs` struct or a `domain_rev` field per substate-scoped `Infra`); substate `bump()` bumps domain + global (global stays for pull-path compatibility). \n   - Domain set (first cut): `podcast.library` (library+categories — the big one), `podcast.playback` (now_playing+queue), `podcast.downloads`, `podcast.inbox`, `podcast.settings`, `podcast.identity`, `podcast.widget`, and a `podcast.misc` catch-all (wiki/picks/clips/transcripts/social/agent/discovery/voice/publish/tasks — small payloads, gate on global rev initially). The per-domain serializers largely already exist as `src/ffi/snapshot_library.rs`, `snapshot_queue.rs`, `snapshot_downloads.rs`, `snapshot_settings.rs`, `snapshot_identity.rs`, `snapshot_widget.rs`, `snapshot_categories.rs` — re-aim them at per-domain envelopes (each carrying its domain rev for shell stale-drop). \n   - Register via `register_typed_snapshot_projection`: closure holds `last_emitted: AtomicU64`; unchanged domain rev → `None` (omitted from frame); changed → JSON bytes in `TypedProjectionData{schema_id: "podcast.library", version: 1}`. \n   - Extend `nmp_app_podcast_decode_update_frame` (`src/ffi/snapshot.rs`) to decode all `podcast.*` sidecars into `v.projections[key]` — clone of the signed_events pattern. \n   - **Tests (non-negotiable, per the #371/#384 lesson):** Rust frame round-trip fixtures per domain + "playback tick frame excludes library" assertion + Swift `KernelDecoding` fixture tests fed by Rust-emitted JSON (snake_case contract — no explicit CodingKeys in embedded types). \n - **PR-3 (M, Swift):** `App/Sources/Bridge/KernelBridge+Callbacks.swift`, `KernelModel.swift`, `KernelDecoding.swift`, `AppStateStore+KernelProjection.swift` — apply per-domain payloads present in the frame instead of triggering `pullPodcastSnapshotIfChanged`; keep pull as cold-start hydration + fallback when a frame carries no podcast keys (staged cutover, never a flag-day). Keep widget/Live-Activity feeds (`applyNowPlayingSnapshot`) wired to the playback domain. \n - **PR-4 (S-M, Android):** `src/android.rs` JNI already returns the decoded JSON envelope, so Kotlin gets the keys for free; update `android/.../KernelBridge.kt` + `PodcastSnapshot.kt` to apply per-domain frames, same pull fallback. \n  \n **Validation (Haiku-verifiable):** yes. `NMP_PERF rust_update … payload_bytes=` log line already exists — build_run_sim with a populated library, play an episode 2 min, assert payload_bytes on playback ticks drops from ~MBs to ~KBs and UI position still advances; screenshot player + library. Android same via adb logcat. Plus cargo + headless harness. \n **Independently landable:** each PR yes. **Conflicts:** owns `register.rs`, `ffi/snapshot*.rs`, `state/*.rs` — nothing else this cycle may touch those. [...]  \n ## Status \n  \n The reviewer's two earlier PRs were already merged into `origin/main` (#396 dead-projection deletion, #399 DomainRevs infra), so I completed the wiring as a fresh PR off current `origin/main`: **#400 — https://github.com/pablof7z/podcast-player/pull/400** (left OPEN for re-review). \n  \n ## The domain-mapping approach (one-place mapping) \n  \n I used the reviewer's preferred "Domain on the Infra handle" design. There are exactly **two single-source maps**, no per-call-site scatter: \n - **`Domain → counter`**: `DomainRevs::counter` (extracted to new `state/domain.rs`) \n - **`Domain → substate`**: `PodcastAppState::new_with_identity` hands each substate a domain-scoped `Infra` via `infra.with_domain(Domain::X)`. `Infra::bump` now reads `self.domain` and advances both that domain's counter and the global rev — so a substate's existing bare `self.infra.bump()` routes correctly with **zero call-site churn**. Scoped: PlaybackState→Playback, CategoriesState→Library, everything else→Misc (default). \n  \n ## bump_domain wiring at mutation sites \n  \n The host-op handler holds the root (Misc) Infra, so its arms can't use scope. I added one handler-side mechanism, `PodcastHostOpHandler::bump_domain(Domain)`, and replaced every raw `self.state.infra.rev.fetch_add(1, …)` with a domain-tagged call across settings_actions (41), player_actions (Playback/Downloads), podcast_actions (Library/Settings), downloads (Downloads/Library), feed + refresh + dispatch (Library), plus `IdentityHandler::with_domain_rev` (Identity) and the cross-thread audio/download report FFIs (Library + Playback). I also moved `inbox` into the library payload since it's derived from library episodes. \n  \n ## End-to-end test result (the proof requested) \n  \n ``` \n test ...::real_queue_mutation_bumps_only_playback_domain ... ok \n test ...::real_settings_mutation_bumps_only_settings_domain ... ok \n ``` \n A real `podcast.player.enqueue` through the actual handler advances **only** the playback domain rev (library + settings unchanged); `set_skip_intervals` advances **only** settings. Combined with the existing `playback_tick_excludes_library_sidecar` (frame omits the library sidecar), this proves a real playback change produces a frame with the playback sidecar and **without** the library sidecar. \n  \n ## Rebase + golden status \n  \n Branched off current `origin/main` (post-#396/#399 merge), so the dead gated projection is already gone — nothing to drop. Golden fixture **3789 bytes, byte-identical** (pull path untouched). `cargo test -p nmp-app-podcast`: **1213 passed, 0 failed, 7 ignored**. clippy: 54 warnings vs baseline 56 (no new warnings; removed two dead items). `state/mod.rs` was split to `state/domain.rs` to stay under the 500-LOC ceiling (558→464). No nmp-core change; `App/` and `android/` untouched. \n  [...]  \n The per-domain frame work is **not just a perf win — the push pipeline is currently dead on BOTH shells**, and on Android it's actively *harmful*: \n  \n - **iOS:** `KernelBridge.decode(pointer:)` (`App/Sources/Bridge/KernelBridge.swift:234-256`) still requires `v.projections["podcast.snapshot"]`. Since NMP v0.3.0 typed-first the generic projections map is never encoded, and #396 deleted that registration. **Every push frame fails decode** ("snapshot frame missing podcast.snapshot projection") and `sink.handler` never fires. iOS today is 100% pull-driven: report-channel hooks + `pullPodcastSnapshotIfChanged` (full multi-MB Rust serialize + full off-main decode per change). Background rev bumps (triage completion, async feed hydration) surface only when an audio report or user dispatch happens to probe. \n - **Android:** worse. `SnapshotCodec.decodeEnvelope` (`PodcastSnapshot.kt:503-525`) decodes the slim `v` (`rev`/`running`/`schema_version` only — see `nmp_app_podcast_decode_update_frame`, `ffi/snapshot.rs:356+`) directly as `PodcastSnapshot`. Every field is defaulted, so decode **succeeds with an empty library** and `MainActivity.kt:152-157` does `snapshot = next` — every kernel emit **clobbers the UI to an empty state**. This is an active correctness bug, masked only by how rarely frames emit while idle. \n - **Kernel contract gap found:** in `ffi/snapshot_domain_projections.rs`, when a domain rev advances but the builder returns `None` (empty state — library/downloads/identity/widget), `last_emitted` is NOT advanced and no tombstone is emitted. Consequences: (a) a shell consuming sidecars can never learn "downloads cleared / signed out / unsubscribed-all"; (b) an empty domain re-runs `build_podcast_update` (full snapshot build, store lock) **every tick forever**. A small Rust fix (emit `{"rev":N, "<field>":null}` and advance `last_emitted`) is required before shells can rely on sidecars. Also note: each domain builder calls full `build_podcast_update` per changed domain per tick (up to 7 full builds/tick) — acceptable post-#267 (~7.6ms), flag as kernel follow-up, not a blocker. [...] User: [Agent task result: Agent "Impl: iOS per-domain push consumption" completed] \n PR is at https://github.com/pablof7z/podcast-player/pull/403. Here is the full report: \n  \n --- \n  \n ## Report \n  \n ### What was done \n  \n The iOS push path was dead: `PodcastHandle.decode(pointer:)` required `v.projections["podcast.snapshot"]` which NMP v0.3.0 stopped encoding (#396 deleted the registration). Every push frame logged "snapshot frame missing podcast.snapshot projection" and the shell fell back to 100% pull-driven operation — full Rust serialize + full off-main decode (~3.9MB / ~35ms per tick). \n  \n ### Decode change (quoted) \n  \n Before: \n ```swift \n guard let update = Self.decodePodcastUpdate(envelopePayload: data) else { \n     kbLog.error("snapshot frame missing podcast.snapshot projection bytes=\(data.count)") \n     return nil \n } \n ``` \n  \n After: \n ```swift \n guard let domainFrames = PodcastDomainFrames.decode(from: data) else { \n     kbLog.error("snapshot frame missing all podcast.* domain sidecars bytes=\(data.count)") \n     return nil \n } \n ``` \n  \n `KernelUpdateResult` now carries `domainFrames: PodcastDomainFrames` instead of `update: PodcastUpdate`. \n  \n ### KernelDomainFrames.swift — one envelope (confirming NO explicit CodingKeys) \n  \n ```swift \n struct PlaybackDomainFrame: Decodable { \n     var rev: UInt64 = 0 \n     var nowPlaying: PlayerState? \n     var queue: [EpisodeSummary]? \n } \n ``` \n  \n No `CodingKeys` enum. `now_playing` → `nowPlaying` and `queue` via `.convertFromSnakeCase` exactly as the #371 contract requires. \n  \n ### Composite merge + per-domain observable assignment + drop-guard \n  \n `KernelModel` holds: \n - `compositeUpdate: PodcastUpdate` — the merged state from selective domain updates \n - `domainRevTracker: DomainRevTracker` — per-domain last-applied rev for drop-guard \n  \n In `apply(result:)`: \n 1. `mergeDomainFrames(_:into:tracker:)` iterates each present domain, compares `frame.rev > tracker.<domain>`, merges only accepted domains, returns `Bool` (any accepted) \n 2. If accepted: `compositeUpdate.rev = max(domain revs)`, `compositeUpdate.running = true`, then `applyPodcastUpdate(compositeUpdate, fromPull: false)` \n 3. Identity: only updated when `result.identity != .empty` (identity domain was present this frame) — preserves prior `kernelIdentity` when identity didn't change \n  \n ### Tombstone handling \n  \n Domain envelopes use `decodeIfPresent` throughout. A frame like `{"rev":99,"active_account":null}` decodes with `activeAccount == nil` (logged-out state). The `mergeDomainFrames` method assigns `composite.activeAccount = ident.activeAccount` (nil = logged out) when the domain's rev advances. \n  \n ### Wire tests \n  \n `KernelBridgeWireTests.swift` gained 9 new test methods: \n 1. `testPlaybackDomainFrameDecodesViaKernelDecodingSeam` — snake_case `episode_id` → `episodeId` \n 2. `testLibraryDomainFrameDecodesViaKernelDecodingSeam` — `is_subscribed` → `isSubscribed` \n 3. `testIdentityDomainFrameDecodesActiveAccountViaSnakeCaseConversion` — `pubkey_hex` → `pubkeyHex` \n 4. `testMultiDomainFrameDecodesAllPresentDomains` \n 5. `testPlaybackOnlyFrameDoesNotClearLibrarySliceInComposite` — core delta-transport assertion \n 6. `testIdentityTombstoneFrameClearsActiveAccount` — `active_account: null` → `activeAccount == nil` \n 7. `testDropGuardIgnoresStaleRevFrame` — rev=3 after rev=5 accepted → composite unchanged \n 8. `testAbsentDomainFrameYieldsNil` — D6 degrade \n 9. `testDomainSchemaConstantsMatchKernelSchemaIDs` \n  \n **What was run**: `xcodebuild build -scheme Podcastr -destination "generic/platform=iOS Simulator" -skipPackagePluginValidation` — zero Swift errors. Build fails only at the linker (missing Rust dylib for this worktree — expected). Could not run the sim tests because the Rust dylib is not built in this worktree. Tests are structured for `xcodebuild test -only-testing:PodcastrTests/KernelBridgeWireTests` once the dylib is available. \n  \n **PR**: https://github.com/pablof7z/podcast-player/pull/403 — left open for review. [...] Independent review complete. This PR fully removes the empty-library clobber bug and ships the Android per-domain push-consumption half as a faithful twin of the already-approved iOS #403. I read every changed file plus the Rust emitter and the iOS twin for cross-checking. \n  \n ### 1. Clobber removed + cold-start — FULLY FIXED, no blank-library path remains \n - The old `decodeFromJsonElement(PodcastSnapshot.serializer(), v)` path is **gone** — the entire `decodeEnvelope` + `SnapshotEnvelope` block was deleted from `PodcastSnapshot.kt` (diff lines 487–535 removed). The slim `v` is never again decoded as a full snapshot. \n - `MainActivity.kt:166-172` applies `snapshot = merged` **only when `anyAccepted == true`**. A frame with no domains returns `null` from `decodeDomainFrames` (the `if (!frames.hasAnyDomain) null` guard, `DomainFrames.kt`), hits `?: continue`, and never touches state. A frame whose domain