mains. Sidecar `rev` is the global rev (Rust `update.rev` for all domains) — same as iOS. Tracker is `remember { DomainRevTracker() }`, resetting to all-0 on process restart; combined with the cold-start pull (which sets full state without advancing the tracker), the first post-launch push for each domain is accepted and merges identical-or-newer data over the pulled snapshot — no drop, no clobber. \n  \n ### 5. Hygiene \n Android-only: diff stat is 3 Kotlin files (`DomainFrames.kt` new, `MainActivity.kt` +20/-8, `PodcastSnapshot.kt` -51 codec removal). No Rust/JNI change. All merge targets (`agentTasks`, `feedbackEvents`, `feedbackThreads`, `voice`, `agent`, etc.) exist on `PodcastSnapshot`. The `MainActivity` edit is minimal and localized to the frame loop (lines 151-173) plus one tracker declaration — it will not conflict heavily with the uncommitted identity WIP in the shared root (that WIP is in the DisposableEffect/identity-restore block, a different region). \n  [...] I found the non-blocking self-dispatch seam: `nmp_app_dispatch_action` only **validates** an action and enqueues an `ActorCommand::DispatchHostOp`, returning immediately — it does NOT round-trip the actor (documented at `tasks_handler.rs:16-23`, and already used by `run_now` and all of `nmp_dispatch.rs`). This is exactly the property the task asked for, so I used the enqueue approach (the preferred option). \n  \n ### New `update_owned` backfill (quoted) \n  \n ```rust \n // Backfill per-episode kind:54 events on a private→public flip by \n // SELF-ENQUEUING one `publish_episode` action per episode (NOT a \n // synchronous loop). Each self-dispatch enqueues an \n // `ActorCommand::DispatchHostOp` and returns immediately, so each episode \n // publishes in its own later actor tick and the actor yields in between — \n // a 50–100 episode flip stays responsive instead of blocking the actor for \n // N sequential Blossom uploads (D8)... \n let episodes_queued = episode_ids_to_backfill.len(); \n let mut episodes_accepted = 0usize; \n for episode_id in episode_ids_to_backfill { \n     let body = serde_json::json!({ "op": "publish_episode", "episode_id": episode_id }); \n     if self_dispatch_publish(handler.app, body) { \n         episodes_accepted += 1; \n     } \n } \n ``` \n  \n New helper `self_dispatch_publish` in `nmp_dispatch.rs` wraps `nmp_app_dispatch_action` for the `podcast.publish` namespace (returns immediately, never blocks). The dispatched `{"op":"publish_episode","episode_id":...}` is the same action the old Swift loop fired via `kernelPublishEpisode` — each lands in its own actor tick. Response carries `episodes_queued` (policy decision, D0-owned) and `episodes_accepted` (FFI accepts). [...] 1. **Rust kernel owns the projection.** `SocialState.nostr_conversations_snapshot()` is the single source of truth — it groups inbound `AgentNoteSummary` records and `OutboundTurn` entries by `root_event_id`, merges turns in timestamp order, sorts conversations newest-first, and computes `trusted` live against the follow set. The `podcast.social` domain is the 8th delta sidecar registered alongside the existing 7. \n  [...]  \n I used the reviewer's preferred "Domain on the Infra handle" design. There are exactly **two single-source maps**, no per-call-site scatter: \n - **`Domain → counter`**: `DomainRevs::counter` (extracted to new `state/domain.rs`) \n - **`Domain → substate`**: `PodcastAppState::new_with_identity` hands each substate a domain-scoped `Infra` via `infra.with_domain(Domain::X)`. `Infra::bump` now reads `self.domain` and advances both that domain's counter and the global rev — so a substate's existing bare `self.infra.bump()` routes correctly with **zero call-site churn**. Scoped: PlaybackState→Playback, CategoriesState→Library, everything else→Misc (default). \n 
