pp-local; zero upstream changes.** \n  \n --- \n  \n ## Item 1 (HEADLINE) — Domain sub-projections as per-domain typed sidecars + per-domain revs \n  [...]   - `src/state/mod.rs`: `Infra` currently carries ONE global `rev: Arc<AtomicU64>` cloned into all 15 substates. Add a per-domain rev (e.g. `DomainRevs` struct or a `domain_rev` field per substate-scoped `Infra`); substate `bump()` bumps domain + global (global stays for pull-path compatibility). \n   - Domain set (first cut): `podcast.library` (library+categories — the big one), `podcast.playback` (now_playing+queue), `podcast.downloads`, `podcast.inbox`, `podcast.settings`, `podcast.identity`, `podcast.widget`, and a `podcast.misc` catch-all (wiki/picks/clips/transcripts/social/agent/discovery/voice/publish/tasks — small payloads, gate on global rev initially). The per-domain serializers largely already exist as `src/ffi/snapshot_library.rs`, `snapshot_queue.rs`, `snapshot_downloads.rs`, `snapshot_settings.rs`, `snapshot_identity.rs`, `snapshot_widget.rs`, `snapshot_categories.rs` — re-aim them at per-domain envelopes (each carrying its domain rev for shell stale-drop). \n   - Register via `register_typed_snapshot_projection`: closure holds `last_emitted: AtomicU64`; unchanged domain rev → `None` (omitted from frame); changed → JSON bytes in `TypedProjectionData{schema_id: "podcast.library", version: 1}`. [...] ### Seam used: self-enqueue (not async-upload, not blocked) \n  \n I found the non-blocking self-dispatch seam: `nmp_app_dispatch_action` only **validates** an action and enqueues an `ActorCommand::DispatchHostOp`, returning immediately — it does NOT round-trip the actor (documented at `tasks_handler.rs:16-23`, and already used by `run_now` and all of `nmp_dispatch.rs`). This is exactly the property the task asked for, so I used the enqueue approach (the preferred option). \n  \n ### New `update_owned` backfill (quoted) \n  \n ```rust \n // Backfill per-episode kind:54 events on a private→public flip by \n // SELF-ENQUEUING one `publish_episode` action per episode (NOT a \n // synchronous loop). Each self-dispatch enqueues an \n // `ActorCommand::DispatchHostOp` and returns immediately, so each episode \n // publishes in its own later actor tick and the actor yields in between — \n // a 50–100 episode flip stays responsive instead of blocking the actor for \n // N sequential Blossom uploads (D8)... \n let episodes_queued = episode_ids_to_backfill.len(); \n let mut episodes_accepted = 0usize; \n for episode_id in episode_ids_to_backfill { \n     let body = serde_json::json!({ "op": "publish_episode", "episode_id": episode_id }); \n     if self_dispatch_publish(handler.app, body) { \n         episodes_accepted += 1; \n     } \n } \n ``` \n  \n New helper `self_dispatch_publish` in `nmp_dispatch.rs` wraps `nmp_app_dispatch_action` for the `podcast.publish` namespace (returns immediately, never blocks). The dispatched `{"op":"publish_episode","episode_id":...}` is the same action the old Swift loop fired via `kernelPublishEpisode` — each lands in its own actor tick. Response carries `episodes_queued` (policy decision, D0-owned) and `episodes_accepted` (FFI accepts). [...] - **Kernel contract gap found:** in `ffi/snapshot_domain_projections.rs`, when a domain rev advances but the builder returns `None` (empty state — library/downloads/identity/widget), `last_emitted` is NOT advanced and no tombstone is emitted. Consequences: (a) a shell consuming sidecars can never learn "downloads cleared / signed out / unsubscribed-all"; (b) an empty domain re-runs `build_podcast_update` (full snapshot build, store lock) **every tick forever**. A small Rust fix (emit `{"rev":N, "<field>":null}` and advance `last_emitted`) is required before shells can rely on sidecars. Also note: each domain builder calls full `build_podcast_update` per changed domain per tick (up to 7 full builds/tick) — acceptable post-#267 (~7.6ms), flag as kernel follow-up, not a blocker. \n  [...] The per-domain frame work is **not just a perf win — the push pipeline is currently dead on BOTH shells**, and on Android it's actively *harmful*: \n  \n - **iOS:** `KernelBridge.decode(pointer:)` (`App/Sources/Bridge/KernelBridge.swift:234-256`) still requires `v.projections["podcast.snapshot"]`. Since NMP v0.3.0 typed-first the generic projections map is never encoded, and #396 deleted that registration. **Every push frame fails decode** ("snapshot frame missing podcast.snapshot projection") and `sink.handler` never fires. iOS today is 100% pull-driven: report-channel hooks + `pullPodcastSnapshotIfChanged` (full multi-MB Rust serialize + full off-main decode per change). Background rev bumps (triage completion, async feed hydration) surface only when an audio report or user dispatch happens to probe. \n - **Android:** worse. `SnapshotCodec.decodeEnvelope` (`PodcastSnapshot.kt:503-525`) decodes the slim `v` (`rev`/`running`/`schema_version` only — see `nmp_app_podcast_decode_update_frame`, `ffi/snapshot.rs:356+`) directly as `PodcastSnapshot`. Every field is defaulted, so decode **succeeds with an empty library** and `MainActivity.kt:152-157` does `snapshot = next` — every kernel emit **clobbers the UI to an empty state**. This is an active correctness bug, masked only by how rarely frames emit while idle. [...] - **Android:** worse. `SnapshotCodec.decodeEnvelope` (`PodcastSnapshot.kt:503-525`) decodes the slim `v` (`rev`/`running`/`schema_version` only — see `nmp_app_podcast_decode_update_frame`, `ffi/snapshot.rs:356+`) directly as `PodcastSnapshot`. Every field is defaulted, so decode **succeeds with an empty library** and `MainActivity.kt:152-157` does `snapshot = next` — every kernel emit **clobbers the UI to an empty state**. This is an active correctness bug, masked only by how rarely frames emit while idle. \n - **Kernel contract gap found:** in `ffi/snapshot_domain_projections.rs`, when a domain rev advances but the builder returns `None` (empty state — library/downloads/identity/widget), `last_emitted` is NOT advanced and no tombstone is emitted. Consequences: (a) a shell consuming sidecars can never learn "downloads cleared / signed out / unsubscribed-all"; (b) an empty domain re-runs `build_podcast_update` (full snapshot build, store lock) **every tick forever**. A small Rust fix (emit `{"rev":N, "<field>":null}` and advance `last_emitted`) is required before shells can rely on sidecars. Also note: each domain builder calls full `build_podcast_update` per changed domain per tick (up to 7 full builds/tick) — acceptable post-#267 (~7.6ms), flag as kernel follow-up, not a blocker. [...] ### Follow-up 1 — cold-start re-seed insurance (`KernelModel.swift`) \n  \n **Approach chosen:** `hasHydrated` flag (cleaner than `>=` unconditionally — it limits the wider allowance to exactly the first cold-start pull, restoring normal `>` for everything after). \n  \n **Change (quoted):** \n ```swift \n // KernelModel.swift — new property \n private var hasHydrated: Bool = false \n  \n // applyPodcastUpdate — new guard \n let revPasses = fromPull && !hasHydrated \n     ? update.rev >= Int(lastProcessedRev) \n     : update.rev > Int(lastProcessedRev) \n guard revPasses else { return } \n lastProcessedRev = UInt64(update.rev) \n if fromPull { \n     compositeUpdate = update \n     hasHydrated = true   // ← steady-state guard restored from here on \n } \n ``` \n  \n `resetAndRestart()` also resets `hasHydrated = false` so a kernel reset gets the same cold-start allowance. No steady-state behaviour change — once the first full pull lands, the normal `>` monotonic guard is in effect for all subsequent push and pull frames. [...] - The old `decodeFromJsonElement(PodcastSnapshot.serializer(), v)` path is **gone** — the entire `decodeEnvelope` + `SnapshotEnvelope` block was deleted from `PodcastSnapshot.kt` (diff lines 487–535 removed). The slim `v` is never again decoded as a full snapshot. \n - `MainActivity.kt:166-172` applies `snapshot = merged` **only when `anyAccepted == true`**. A frame with no domains returns `null` from `decodeDomainFrames` (the `if (!frames.hasAnyDomain) null` guard, `DomainFrames.kt`), hits `?: continue`, and never touches state. A frame whose domains are all stale yields `anyAccepted=false` → no assignment. \n - Cold-start hydrator is intact: `MainActivity.kt:140-148` still does the one-shot `bridge.podcastSnapshot()` PULL → `SnapshotCodec.decode` (the full-snapshot decoder, retained). The grid paints on launch. \n - Absent domains are merged via `copy()` touching only present slices — they are never cleared. **The empty-clobber is fully removed, not narrowed.** There is no remaining path where a push frame blanks the library: blanking now requires an explicit library tombstone (`{"rev":N,"library":null}`) at a higher rev, which is the intended all-unsubscribed signal. \n  \n ### 2. Schema symmetry — `@SerialName` ↔ Rust emitted fields (per-domain table) \n  \n Rust emitter: `apps/nmp-app-podcast/src/ffi/snapshot_domain_projections.rs`. `ignoreUnknownKeys = true` is set (`DomainFrames.kt` SnapshotCodec.json), so Rust-only fields are safely dropped on Android. All Kotlin domain-frame fields are nullable/defaulted → no missing-required throw risk. \n  \n | Domain | Rust emits | Kotlin `@SerialName` | Match | \n |---|---|---|---| \n | library | rev, library, categories, search_results, nostr_results, owned_podcasts, inbox, inbox_triage_in_progress | rev, library, `search_results`, inbox, `inbox_triage_in_progress` | ✅ (categories/nostr_results/owned_podcasts intentionally not modeled on Android — no top-level field exists, same as iOS-renders-only superset; harmless via ignoreUnknownKeys) | \n | playback | rev, now_playing, queue | rev, `now_playing`, queue | ✅ | \n | downloads | rev, downloads | rev, downloads | ✅ | \n | settings | rev, settings, configured_relays | rev, settings | ✅ (configured_relays not modeled on Android, as in base snapshot) | \n | identity | rev, active_account | rev, `active_account` | ✅ | \n | widget | rev, widget | rev, widget | ✅ | \n | misc | rev, +15 fields | rev, `agent_tasks`, `feedback_events`, `feedback_threads`, voice, agent | ✅ subset (wiki/picks/clips/social/etc. not rendered on Android) | \n  \n Nested types (`NowPlayingState`, `DownloadQueueSnapshot`, `EpisodeSummary`, `PodcastSummary`, `AccountSummary`, `WidgetSnapshot`, `InboxItem`) are **unchanged, pre-existing** types already proven by the working cold-start `decode` pull path; the domain frames reuse them, inheriting correct `@SerialName`s. No mismatch found. \n  \n ### 3. Tombstone handling — correct \n `coerceInputValues = true` does **not** corrupt tombstones because every tombstone primary field is nullable (`library: List<...>? = null`, `downloads`, `activeAccount`, `widget`) — null stays null, no throw. Merge maps: library null → `emptyList()`, identity null → `activeAccount = null` (signed out), downloads null → `downloads = null`, widget null → `widget = null`. Matches the Rust tombstone shapes exactly. \n  \n ### 4. Drop guard + merge — correct \n Per-domain `frame.rev > tracker[domain]` monotonic guard; `copy()` replaces only accepted domains. Sidecar `rev` is the global rev (Rust `update.rev` for all domains) — same as iOS. Tracker is `remember { DomainRevTracker() }`, resetting to all-0 on process restart; combined with the cold-start pull (which sets full state without advancing the tracker), the first post-launch push for each domain is accepted and merges identical-or-newer data over the pulled snapshot — no drop, no clobber. \n  \n ### 5. Hygiene \n Android-only: diff stat is 3 Kotlin files (`DomainFrames.kt` new, `MainActivity.kt` +20/-8, `PodcastSnapshot.kt` -51 codec removal). No Rust/JNI change. All merge targets (`agentTasks`, `feedbackEvents`, `feedbackThreads`, `voice`, `agent`, etc.) exist on `PodcastSnapshot`. The `MainActivity` edit is minimal and localized to the frame loop (lines 151-173) plus one tracker declaration — it will not conflict heavily with the uncommitted identity WIP in the shared root (that WIP is in the DisposableEffect/identity-restore block, a different region). [...] ## The durable fix \n  \n Extracted the per-episode `EpisodeSummary` construction out of `build_library_snapshot` into a shared helper, so both the full-library path and the slice-local queue builder produce rows the exact same way — byte-identity by construction, not by copying field-by-field. \n  \n **Shared helper signature** (in `apps/nmp-app-podcast/src/ffi/snapshot_library.rs`): \n ```rust \n pub(super) fn episode_summary( \n     handle: &PodcastHandle, \n     store: &PodcastStore, \n     podcast: &Podcast, \n     ep: &Episode, \n     transcripts: &HashMap<String, Vec<TranscriptEntry>>, \n     categories_cache: &HashMap<String, Vec<String>>, \n ) -> EpisodeSummary \n ``` \n  \n - `build_library_snapshot` now calls it per episode (its 50-line inline block collapsed to one `.map(...)`). \n - `build_queue_rows_from_store` now calls the same helper for each matched queued episode, threading in the `transcripts` + `categories_cache` snapshots that `build_playback_payload` takes (same caches the library path uses). It stays slice-local — only the queued episodes are resolved, never a full rebuild over all episodes. \n - The row `id` and `metadata_indexed` lookup now both use the lowercase `ep.id.0.to_string()`, matching the library path exactly. Hardcoded empties (`description: None`, `chapters: Vec::new()`, `ai_categories`, `ad_segments`, `triage_*`, `transcript_status`) are gone. \n  \n ## New regression test \n  \n `apps/nmp-app-podcast/src/ffi/snapshot_domain_queue_identity_tests.rs` — `queue_row_byte_identical_to_full_snapshot_for_content_rich_episode`. Enqueues an episode with an HTML description, chapters, and a transcript, then asserts the slice-local `build_playback_payload` queue equals `serde_json::to_value(build_podcast_update().queue)`. It also sanity-checks the row actually carries description/chapters/transcript and a lowercase id (so a future change that drops fields on *both* paths can't pass silently). Placed in its own file so neither test file exceeds the 500-line limit. \n  \n ## Verification \n  \n - `cargo test -p nmp-app-podcast` — **1273 passed; 0 failed; 7 ignored** (was 1272; +1 new test). \n - `snapshot_bytes_match_golden_fixture` — still passing, golden unchanged (no fixture edit). \n - No wire/DTO change — `EpisodeSummary` fields untouched, so no codegen drift; no generated Swift files in the diff. \n - `git diff --check` clean; all source files under the hard limit (store_helpers 179, builders 334, snapshot_library 128, queue_identity_tests 162, projections 339).
