t-agnostic (single shared file; dedup by globally-unique event-id, turn-cap by global root-id; cross-account carryover can only SUPPRESS, never over-reply = fail-safe; must persist across identity switches, unlike the account-scoped social state cleared in `register.rs`): on the `ResponderCache` struct def and at the restore site in `ffi/data_dir.rs`. \n  \n **Verification** (real output): \n - `cargo test -p nmp-app-podcast agent_note_responder` → `result: ok. 13 passed; 0 failed` (10 prior + 3 new cap/ring tests, all green). \n - `cargo test -p nmp-app-podcast golden` → `snapshot_bytes_match_golden_fixture ... ok` — fixture byte-identical (no snapshot/projection/DTO touched). \n  [...] **Trust policy (the security decision): `trust(pubkey) = (followed(pubkey) OR approved(pubkey)) AND NOT blocked(pubkey)`.** \n - **Block is an absolute override** (even a followed pubkey, if explicitly blocked, is untrusted and gets no auto-reply). This gives the user a hard kill-switch independent of their kind:3. \n - **An approved-but-unfollowed sender IS auto-replied to.** Justification (D0/security): approval is an *explicit, deliberate, kernel-recorded user act* naming that exact pubkey — it carries strictly *more* intent than a follow (a follow is a broad social signal, often bulk-imported; an approval is a per-peer "yes, this agent may converse with mine"). The auto-responder already has hard runaway defenses independent of trust source: per-root turn cap `MAX_OUTGOING_TURNS_PER_ROOT=10` (`agent_note_responder.rs:69`), `wtd-end` gate, and dedup. So promoting approved→auto-reply does not widen the blast radius beyond what a follow already permits, while the block override *narrows* it. This is the durable, least-surprising policy: the approval surface a user sees becomes the thing that actually governs auto-reply, eliminating finding #2's orphaning. \n 
