 Swift-build experiment; the shared root is untouched. [...] PR is open: **https://github.com/pablof7z/podcast-player/pull/426** \n  \n Here is what shipped in this atomic PR: \n  \n **Rust kernel (`nmp-app-podcast`)** \n  \n - `/apps/nmp-app-podcast/src/store/approved_peer_store.rs` (new) — `ApprovedPeerStore` with JSON persistence, atomic write, D6 load, full inline test suite \n - `/apps/nmp-app-podcast/src/state/social.rs` — `trust_predicate()` closure implementing `(followed || approved) && !blocked`; four mutation helpers; truth-table tests for all combinations \n - `/apps/nmp-app-podcast/src/ffi/actions/social_module.rs` — four new `SocialAction` variants \n - `/apps/nmp-app-podcast/src/host_op_handler/social_actions.rs` — match arms: mutate → persist → `infra.bump()` → `{"ok":true}` \n - `ffi/handle.rs`, `ffi/register.rs`, `ffi/data_dir.rs`, `agent_note_handler.rs` — wiring throughout \n  \n **iOS (Swift)** \n  \n - `/App/Sources/Bridge/KernelModel+Social.swift` (new) — four dispatch shims to `podcast.social` \n - `AppStateStore+Nostr.swift` — routes through kernel, removes pending-approval management \n - `AppStateStore+Friends.swift` — `addFriend`/`removeFriend` dispatch to kernel \n - `AppState.swift` — `nostrPendingApprovals` field/CodingKey/decoder line deleted \n - `NostrPendingApproval.swift` and `NostrApprovalPresenter.swift` — deleted \n - `AgentAccessControlView.swift` — two-tab (Allowed/Blocked), no pending tab \n - `AgentWhitelistRows.swift` — `PendingApprovalRow` removed \n - `RootView.swift` — `.nostrApprovalPresenter()` call removed \n - `AgentSettingsView.swift`, `SettingsView.swift` — stale badge counts removed \n  \n Assistant: #2 implementor is applying both fixes (the action-path re-emit test + fail-closed-on-poisoned-lock at both predicate sites). When it returns I'll verify the new test drives the real `handle_social_action` seam (not a direct call or `fetch_add`) and that block stays absolute, then merge. \n  \n **Session tally:** 5 PRs merged (cycle-8 A/B/C; cycle-9 #1/#3), #2 (#426) in final review-fix. Cycle-9's remaining follow-ups (Android conversations UI, kind:0 `claimProfile`-on-appear, flat `agent_notes` wire retirement, NIP-46) are smaller and queued for the next tick. Disk healthy, 2h cron loop active. Holding for #2's amended push. \n  \n User: [Agent task result: Agent "Implement Cycle-9 #2: kernel approve/block" completed] \n Both review items are fixed, verified, and force-pushed. Here is the report. \n  \n ## FIX 1 — action-path re-emit test (the #423-class end-to-end guard) \n  \n Added two tests in `apps/nmp-app-podcast/src/ffi/snapshot_domain_projection_tests.rs`, both driving the action through the REAL `PodcastHostOpHandler::handle_social_action` dispatch (the same entry the FFI router uses) — never `state.approve_peer()` directly and never a manual `domain_revs.social.fetch_add`: \n  \n - **`approve_peer_action_reemits_social_with_trusted_flipped_real_path`** \n   Seeds an inbound note from a non-followed peer (conversation projects `trusted:false`), drains the sidecar to idle, then dispatches `SocialAction::ApprovePeer` through the handler. Asserts `podcast.social` RE-EMITS with that conversation's `trusted` now `true`. \n - **`block_peer_action_reemits_social_with_trusted_false_overriding_follow`** \n   Wires a follow set containing the peer (conversation projects `trusted:true`), dispatches `SocialAction::BlockPeer` through the handler, asserts the re-emit flips `trusted` to `false` (block is absolute, overriding follow). \n  \n A new helper `make_handle_and_state_with_approved` builds state with `social.approved` wired the same way `register.rs` does (before the `Arc` wrap), so the action handler, the trust predicate, and the projection all read one shared store. \n  \n **Test output (real action path):** \n ``` \n test ffi::snapshot_domain_projections::tests::approve_peer_action_reemits_social_with_trusted_flipped_real_path ... ok \n test ffi::snapshot_domain_projections::tests::block_peer_action_reemits_social_with_trusted_false_overriding_follow ... ok \n ``` \n  \n **Mutation-guard proof:** I temporarily removed `self.state.social.infra.bump()` from the ApprovePeer arm and re-ran — the test failed exactly as intended (`ApprovePeer action MUST re-emit podcast.social ... panicked at ...:821`), then restored the bump and confirmed `social_actions.rs` is byte-identical to the committed version (it is NOT in the diff). \n  \n ## FIX 2 — fail CLOSED on a poisoned approved-store mutex \n  \n Both duplicated sites changed from fail-OPEN to fail-CLOSED: \n  \n - `apps/nmp-app-podcast/src/state/social.rs` `trust_predicate()` — on `lock().is_err()` sets `fail_closed = true`; the returned predicate returns `false` for every pubkey (cannot prove a peer is not blocked → deny everyone). \n - `apps/nmp-app-podcast/src/agent_note_handler.rs` responder gate (~:424) — same `fail_closed` flag folded into the trusted expression, so a poisoned lock never auto-responds. \n  \n Added `trust_predicate_fails_closed_on_poisoned_approved_lock`: poisons the mutex (panic-on-thread holding the lock), then asserts a FOLLOWED peer becomes untrusted. Passes: \n ``` \n test state::social::tests::trust_predicate_fails_closed_on_poisoned_approved_lock ... ok \n ``` \n  \n ## Verification \n  \n - `cargo test -p nmp-app-podcast` — **1294 passed, 0 failed** (was 1291; +3 new tests). \n - Golden — `snapshot_bytes_match_golden_fixture ... ok` (byte-identical). \n - No new wire field, no codegen/Swift drift (`git status` shows zero generated/Swift changes) — Rust-only logic changes, no iOS rebuild needed. \n - `git diff --check` — clean. \n - Disk: ran `cargo clean -p nmp-app-podcast` (6.1Gi → 7.8Gi free). \n - Amended + `git push --force-with-lease` succeeded (`70ecf2c1...009bd64a`). All work confined to the worktree; the shared root was never touched. \n  [...] 📋 SUMMARY: v1 vertical = kernel-owned approve/block allow-list on `podcast.social`, unioned into the live trust predicate the responder + projection already share, with the orphaned iOS approval surface wired to those kernel actions; kind:0 hydration and Android render are clean follow-ups. \n  \n 🔍 ANALYSIS (verified against `origin/main` @ b9ce9a68): \n  \n 1. **Trust is 100% follow-set, with no manual-approval path.** `ActiveFollowSet` (`~/.cargo/git/.../6418a7a/crates/nmp-nip02/src/active_follow_set.rs`) is populated *only* from the active account's kind:3 `p`-tags plus self. Its `predicate()` (line ~186) reads a private `Arc<RwLock<BTreeSet<String>>>` and has **no public mutation API**. Both the responder gate (`agent_note_handler.rs:417` → `agent_note_responder.rs:380`) and the projection (`state/social.rs:171,276`) call this one predicate. So there is exactly one trust decision and it cannot be influenced by an approval today. \n  \n 2. **The Swift approval surface is fully orphaned scaffolding.** `AppState.swift:35-37` holds `nostrAllowedPubkeys`/`nostrBlockedPubkeys`/`nostrPendingApprovals` (Codable-persisted). `AppStateStore+Nostr.swift` mutates them; `AgentAccessControlView.swift` (reachable from `AgentSettingsView.swift:92`) and `NostrApprovalPresenter` (wired in `RootView.swift:195`) read them. But: (a) `addNostrPendingApproval` / `NostrPendingApproval(...)` have **no production call site** — nothing ever populates the queue; and (b) the allow/block sets gate **nothing** — no FFI dispatch, and the kernel responder never sees them. This is exactly the "dormant scaffolding" the project rejects. This is the real gap the planner intuited. \n  \n 3. **`AgentNotesView.swift` is NOT the inbound Nostr feed.** It renders local personal `Note`/`NoteKind` from `store.activeNotes` — unrelated to the `agent_notes` wire field. **Do not retire it.** The flat `agent_notes` *wire field* is consumed only by `KernelModel+DomainMerge.swift:161` into `composite.agentNotes`; no UI binds it meaningfully now that conversations exist. The planner's "retire AgentNotesView" premise is wrong; the correct deletion target is the flat `agentNotes` wire field + the orphaned Swift approval state — and that is **follow-up, not v1** (see boundary). \n  \n 4. **kind:0 hydration is already solved durably via `resolved_profiles`.** `claimProfile` (`KernelModel.swift:731`) → kernel resolves → `projections.resolved_profiles` → `mergeResolvedProfiles` (`AppStateStore+KernelProjection.swift:462`) → `nostrProfileCache`. `NostrConversationsView.swift:38` and `NostrConversationDetailView.swift:21` already read `nostrProfileCache[hex]`. **Decision: do NOT hydrate names inside the conversation projection.** Riding the existing `resolved_profiles` seam is the durable answer — duplicating kind:0 into `podcast.social` would create a second profile cache and violate single-source-of-truth. kind:0 is therefore **out of v1** with a tiny follow-up (have the views `claimProfile(counterpartyHex)` on appear if not already). \n  \n 5. **Persistence + re-emit patterns are well-established.** `store/outbound_turn_cache.rs` and `store/agent_note_responder_cache.rs` are the exact model for a new disk sidecar (atomic tmp-rename, D6 load-empty-on-corrupt, seeded from `data_dir.rs:165-193`, shared `Arc<Mutex>` from `register.rs`). The social sidecar emit lives in `snapshot_domain_builders.rs:220 build_social_payload` gated on `domain_revs.social`; the **real-bump rule** (memory `per_domain_projection_real_bump`, which bit #423) means an approve/block action MUST call `state.social.infra.bump()` at the real action site. \n  \n 🎛️ ARCHITECTURE DECISION: \n  \n **Introduce a kernel-owned, per-account, disk-persisted `ApprovedPeerStore` (allow-list + block-list of hex pubkeys), and compose it with `ActiveFollowSet` into a single unified trust predicate** that both the responder and the projection consume. `ActiveFollowSet` stays untouched (it's an upstream NMP crate — do not fork). The union happens **in the podcast app**, in `SocialState`, where the predicate is already built. \n  \n **Trust policy (the security decision): `trust(pubkey) = (followed(pubkey) OR approved(pubkey)) AND NOT blocked(pubkey)`.** \n - **Block is an absolute override** (even a followed pubkey, if explicitly blocked, is untrusted and gets no auto-reply). This gives the user a hard kill-switch independent of their kind:3. \n - **An approved-but-unfollowed sender IS auto-replied to.** Justification (D0/security): approval is an *explicit, deliberate, kernel-recorded user act* naming that exact pubkey — it carries strictly *more* intent than a follow (a follow is a broad social signal, often bulk-imported; an approval is a per-peer "yes, this agent may converse with mine"). The auto-responder already has hard runaway defenses independent of trust source: per-root turn cap `MAX_OUTGOING_TURNS_PER_ROOT=10` (`agent_note_responder.rs:69`), `wtd-end` gate, and dedup. So promoting approved→auto-reply does not widen the blast radius beyond what a follow already permits, while the block override *narrows* it. This is the durable, least-surprising policy: the approval surface a user sees becomes the thing that actually governs auto-reply, eliminating finding #2's orphaning. \n  \n **Why the union lives in `SocialState`, not in `ActiveFollowSet`:** `ActiveFollowSet` is upstream (`nmp-nip02`), pinned by rev; forking it to add an allow-list inverts ownership and breaks the NMP-sync discipline. The app already owns the composition: `SocialState` holds `follow_set: Option<Arc<ActiveFollowSet>>` and builds `predicate` once per projection. We add `approved: Option<Arc<Mutex<ApprovedPeerStore>>>` beside it and replace the two predicate-build sites with a single `trust_predicate()` helper that closes over both. The responder path (`agent_note_handler.rs:415`) gets the same composed predicate injected via `with_responder`, replacing its raw `fs.predicate()`. \n  \n 📐 KERNEL ACTION SHAPE: \n  \n Extend the existing `SocialAction` enum (`ffi/actions/social_module.rs`) — same `#[serde(tag="op", rename_all="snake_case")]` shape, routed through the existing `"podcast.social"` arm at `router.rs:164`: \n - `ApprovePeer { pubkey_hex: String }` \n - `BlockPeer { pubkey_hex: String }` \n - `RemoveApproval { pubkey_hex: String }` / `RemoveBlock { pubkey_hex: String }` \n  \n Handled in `host_op_handler/social_actions.rs` (`handle_social_action`), which mutates `self.state.social`'s approved store, persists via `save_approved_peer_store(data_dir, …)`, then calls `self.state.social.infra.bump()` (the **real-bump** site → re-projects `podcast.social` with flipped `trusted`). Approve clears any block for that hex and vice-versa (mirror the Swift semantics in `AppStateStore+Nostr.swift`). \n  \n ⚡ ORDERED FILE-LEVEL TASK LIST (one atomic PR; clean 2-PR split noted): \n  \n **Rust — store + state (PR-1 core):** \n 1. NEW `apps/nmp-app-podcast/src/store/approved_peer_store.rs` — `ApprovedPeerStore { approved: BTreeSet<String>, blocked: BTreeSet<String> }`; `approve/block/remove_approval/remove_block/is_approved/is_blocked`; `APPROVED_PEER_STORE_FILE="approved-peers.json"`; `load_approved_peer_store(&Path)` (D6 empty-on-corrupt) + `save_approved_peer_store(&Path,&_)` (atomic tmp-rename). Copy `outbound_turn_cache.rs` structure verbatim. Register `pub mod approved_peer_store;` in `store/mod.rs`. Add unit tests inline (`#[path]`). \n 2. `state/social.rs` — add field `approved: Option<Arc<Mutex<ApprovedPeerStore>>>`; builder `with_approved_peers(...)`; NEW private `fn trust_predicate(&self) -> Arc<dyn Fn(&str)->bool+Send+Sync>` implementing `(followed||approved)&&!blocked` over clones of the follow-set predicate + the approved store Arc. Replace the two `self.follow_set.as_ref().map(|fs| fs.predicate())` sites (lines ~171, ~232/276) with `self.trust_predicate()`. Add approve/block mutating methods that lock the store and (caller persists). Add `clear_for_account_switch` handling? **No** — approved peers are per-account *durable*, keyed by account in the data dir, so they must 